streamlines2D

  • streamlines2D(protoOptions: any): { run: () => void }

  • Parameters

    • protoOptions: any

      of the form:

      {
     boundingBox: {
         left  : -5, 
         top   : -5, 
         width : 10, 
         height: 10
     },
     vectorField      : value,
     onStreamlineAdded: value,
     onPointAdded     : value,
     forwardOnly      : value,
     seed             : Vector
     dSep             : number, // Separation between streamlines. Naming according to the paper
     dTest            : number, // When should we stop integrating a streamline
     timeStep         : 0.01,
     stepsPerIteration: 10,
     maxTimePerIteration: 1000
}

    Returns { run: () => void }

    • run: () => void
        • (): void

        • Returns void

createSurface

  • createSurface(__namedParameters: { indices: IArray | Serie; material?: Material; parameters?: SurfaceParameters; positions: IArray | Serie }): Mesh
  • brief

    Generate a 3D surface from positions and indices

    example
    const surface = createSurface({
    positions: dataframe.get('positions'),
    indices  : dataframe.get('indices'),
    parameters: new SurfaceParameters({
        color: '#ff0000',
        flat: true,
        opacity: 0.7,
        creaseAngle: 30 // in degrees
    })
})

const attribute = dataframe.get('U').map( u => u[0] )
paintAttribute(surface, attribute )

const skin = createIsoContourLines({
    geometry : surface.geometry,
    attribute: attribute,
    parameters: new IsoContoursParameters({
        color: '#999900',
        nbr: 10,
        min; 0.2,
        max: 0.8
    })
})

scene.add( surface )
surface.add( skin )

    Parameters

    • __namedParameters: { indices: IArray | Serie; material?: Material; parameters?: SurfaceParameters; positions: IArray | Serie }
      • indices: IArray | Serie
      • Optional material?: Material
      • Optional parameters?: SurfaceParameters
      • positions: IArray | Serie

    Returns Mesh

paintAttribute

  • paintAttribute(mesh: Object3D, attribute: Serie, parameters?: PaintParameters): void
  • brief

    Paint a pointset, a lineset or a surface using a scalar attribute provided by a Serie from the library @youwol/dataframe

    example
    const surface = io.loadGocad(filename)[0] // a dataframe I think

let mesh = createSurface({
     positions: surface.get('positions'),
     indices  : surface.get('indices')
})

paintAttribute(mesh, surface.get('U').map( u => u[0] ) )

    Parameters

    • mesh: Object3D
    • attribute: Serie
    • Optional parameters: PaintParameters

    Returns void

Utils Functions

generateIsos

  • generateIsos(min: number, max: number, nbrOrSpacing?: number, useSpacing?: boolean): number[]

  • Generate iso-values given a min, max and the number of isos to generate

    Parameters

    • min: number

      The minimum value

    • max: number

      The maximum value

    • nbrOrSpacing: number = 10

      Represent either the number of iso-contours (useSpacing=false) or the spacing between iso-contours (useSpacing=true).

    • useSpacing: boolean = false

      If the generation is using or not the spacing between iso-contours. Also, the generated iso values are snapped to zero in both cases.

    Returns number[]

generateIsosByNumber

  • generateIsosByNumber(min: number, max: number, nbr?: number): number[]

  • Generate iso-values given the min, max and the number

    Parameters

    • min: number
    • max: number
    • nbr: number = 10

    Returns number[]

generateIsosBySpacing

  • generateIsosBySpacing(min: number, max: number, spacing: number): number[]

  • Generate iso-values by using spacing. Also, iso-values are snapped to zero, meaning that they alway pass through zero even if 0 is not part of the iso values.

    Parameters

    • min: number
    • max: number
    • spacing: number

    Returns number[]

Const lerp

  • lerp(t: number, min: number, max: number): number
  • brief

    Linearly interpolates between two values. This name is a contraction of "linear interpolation"

    example
    lerp(0  , 1, 5) // 1
lerp(0.5, 1, 5) // 3
lerp(1  , 1, 5) // 5

    Parameters

    • t: number

      The parameter t is clamped to the range [0, 1]

    • min: number

      The minimum value

    • max: number

      The minimum value

    Returns number
